{
  "answer": "In Charles Comte's *Traité de Législation Vol I*, Chapter 13 is dedicated to this distinction, titled \"Distinction between an arbitrary regime and a legal regime. Of what constitutes the difference.\"[^1]\n\nThe core passage introducing the distinction equates a despotic (arbitrary) regime with one where power acts without prior description (i.e., unwritten or irregular), versus a regime of law where power's action is described in advance (i.e., written and more regular): \n\n> A distinction has been made between peoples subject to arbitrary powers and those subject to legal powers; and between despotic governments and governments that act in conformity with the laws. There is often less difference between the one and the other than one is generally inclined to believe: a nation can pass from an arbitrary regime to what is called a legal regime, without being much better off for it.[^2]\n\nComte elaborates that both regimes are ultimately powers (forces) acting on people, composed of similar elements (e.g., ideas, passions, needs of rulers). The key difference lies not in benevolence—one can be as oppressive as the other—but in regularity: an arbitrary regime is irregular and disordered (like a steam engine without a regulator), while a legal regime is uniform due to advance descriptions of its actions (like adding a regulator).[^3]\n\n[^1]: Charles Comte, *Traité de Législation Vol I*, [Chapter 13](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-i-7e62a2/13-distinction-entre-un-regime-arbitraire-et-un-regim/translation/).\n\n[^2]: Charles Comte, *Traité de Législation Vol I*, [paragraph](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-i-7e62a2/13-distinction-entre-un-regime-arbitraire-et-un-regim/translation/#p-0df0fa).\n\n[^3]: Charles Comte, *Traité de Législation Vol I*, [paragraphs](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-i-7e62a2/13-distinction-entre-un-regime-arbitraire-et-un-regim/translation/#p-15c9b0#p-49acb2#p-5af487#p-f2d9cd#p-0df0fa#p-8228a4).",
